rdf:Description.lla:note: Note 1 - the entry written in the Crew agreement is the Westridge.
Note 1 - The registered port of the Border Maid is writen as Lerwick in the Crew Agreemen andregistered at Berwick in 1870.

Note 1 - Mary Helen registered at Fowey and Dartmouth in 1870. Note 2 - There is a wriitten note accompanying the "Discharged" statement which says "In Capt to ship" and on pages 8 & 9 of the official ships log, there is an incident recorded against Charles Libby in Memel, where he sustained stab wounds whilst on unauthorised shore leave and had to be subsequently hospitalised.

Note 1 - The Crew agreement document has the name as Canpulus, but there is no such vessel on CLIP for any port. The entry on the Crew agreement has SS after the vessel name, signifying a steam Ship. The Canopus steam ship was finished in 1871 and registered at the port of Liverpool.
Note 1 - Crew Agreement details completed but did not join the ship.

Note 1 - There was no registration for a vessel named the Vale of Calder for Liverpool in 187- or 1880. Vale of Calder built in 1879 and registered at Waterford. Looks like abbreviated form of used for port of registry-Lpl
Note 1 - No other info pertaining to John Phillips provided on either the Crew agreement document or the Official Log Book.
Note 1 - John Richards did not sign his release from the vessel and there is a note to this effect on the Crew Agreement document.
Note 1 - There is no registration for a vessel by the name of Dumfries at Liverpool for 1860-1880 inclusive. There is a registration for the Dumfriesshire registered in Dumfries.
Note 1 - spelling of birthplace is down as Tyree
